end ! material

! material 3
Clay

    k isotropic
    1.0e-6

    porosity
    0.51

    specific storage
    1.2e-7

!   Note: unsaturated functions (e.g. Brooks-Corey is used here) are a computationally expensive way of
!   generating soil-retention curves. We suggest using the 'generate tables from unsaturated functions' command
!   in your initial model run. This command will use the selected unsaturated function to create/write unsaturated tables to a file. 
!   These lookup tables can then replace the computationally expensive functions in subsequent model runs. 

    unsaturated brooks-corey functions

    air entry pressure
    -0.016

    pore connectivity
    2.0

    residual saturation
    0.183

    !lambda = 0.042
    !eta = 2.12
    !where, eta = 2 + 3(lambda) and  K(h) = K_sat * ((h_b)/h)^eta. I think these are
    !the standard Brooks and Corey equations ...
    exponent
    2.12

!   Command description: "Generate tables from unsaturated functions"    
!   The following command will generate basic lookup tables for flow parameters in the variably saturated zone. 
!   The file R5.p_s_table.clay.dat containing pressure-saturation table will be generated when you run grok.exe. 
!   The file R5.s_k_table.clay.dat containing saturation-relative permeability table will be generated when you run grok.exe. 
!   These tables can then be incorporated into the *.mprops file, removing the computational load of unsaturated functions in subsequent model runs. 
    !Generate tables from unsaturated functions

!   Command description: "Use tabulated unsaturated functions"
!   Similar to the "Generate tables from unsaturated functions" command described above, "Use tabulated unsaturated functions" will substitute
!   the previously defined unsaturated function with tables defining the pressure-saturation and saturation-relative permeability relationship. 
!   The benefit of this command is that it doesn't require user intervention to substitute the tables into subsequent model runs, it will automatically use the generated tables. 
    Use tabulated unsaturated functions

end functions

end ! material